---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "../components/ui/Header.astro";

---

<Layout title="Manifesto | Agora" description="A distributed movement to reclaim the commons and combat digital atomization.">
  
  <article class="pt-32 pb-24 px-6 bg-olive-50 text-olive-900 antialiased">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-16">
      
      <Header>
        <span slot="surtitle">
          A Coordinated Strategy
        </span>
        <fragment slot="header">
          The Manifesto
        </fragment>
        <fragment slot="subtitle">
          The first step in reclaiming the world is looking away from the screen.
        </fragment>
      </Header>

      <section class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 py-12 border-y border-olive-200">
        <div class="p-8 bg-white rounded-3xl border border-olive-100 shadow-sm transition-transform hover:-translate-y-1">
          <h3 class="text-amber-600 font-bold mb-4 uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-[10px]">The Privatization of Time</h3>
          <p class="text-6xl font-bold text-olive-950 mb-2 tracking-tight">6h 40m</p>
          <p class="text-olive-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">Spent online daily by the average human. We are reclaiming those <span class="font-bold text-olive-900">46 hours a week</span> for the commons.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-8 bg-white rounded-3xl border border-olive-100 shadow-sm transition-transform hover:-translate-y-1">
          <h3 class="text-amber-600 font-bold mb-4 uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-[10px]">The Loneliness Tax</h3>
          <p class="text-6xl font-bold text-olive-950 mb-2 tracking-tight">200%</p>
          <p class="text-olive-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">Increase in reported social isolation for heavy digital users. We replace <span class="font-bold text-olive-900">algorithms with Sponsors</span>.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="space-y-18">
        
        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-xs font-mono font-bold text-amber-600 uppercase tracking-widest">1. The Loneliness Epidemic</h2>
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold text-olive-950 tracking-tight">Cheap Thrills and Weak Bonds</h3>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed text-lg">
            Digital tools have made us more connected than ever before, but we’ve never experienced such high levels of loneliness and isolation. Digital platforms addict us to endless supplies of cheap entertainment and shallow social connections, while privatization threatens to undermine our access to common physical spaces.</p>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed text-lg">
            This is not an accident. An atomized population—one that interacts only through mediated, monetized channels—is a population that cannot organize.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-xs font-mono font-bold text-amber-600 uppercase tracking-widest">2. Reclaiming Public Space</h2>
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold text-olive-950 tracking-tight">Fighting for the Commons</h3>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed text-lg">
If we want to change our relationship with society and technology, personal lifestyle changes are not enough. Our digital spaces are designed to monetize and commodify our lives because they are private spaces, owned and designed by private interests — just as our offline communities increasingly are as well. The only way to change the way that these spaces are designed is to <strong>change their ownership</strong>.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="p-8 bg-white border border-olive-200 rounded-3xl shadow-sm space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-xs font-mono font-bold text-amber-600 uppercase tracking-widest">3. Popular Education</h2>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-olive-950">The Study Circle</h3>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed">
            The core of political development in the Agora Project is the <strong class="text-amber-700">study circle</strong>, a tool of popular education that emphasizes a non-hierarchical approach to share knowledge and build a shared identity.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-10 p-10 md:p-14 bg-olive-900 rounded-[3rem] text-olive-50 shadow-2xl relative overflow-hidden">
          <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-32 h-32 bg-amber-500/10 blur-[80px]"></div>
          
          <div class="space-y-2">
            <h2 class="text-xs font-mono font-bold text-amber-400 uppercase tracking-widest">4. Structure</h2>
            <h3 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight">Distributed, Not Centralized</h3>
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-olive-200 leading-relaxed text-lg">
            Traditional community organizing often relies on staff-heavy structures that depend on private funding. Agora operates on a distributed organizing model to ensure political indpendence and democratic governance.
          </p>
          
          <ul class="space-y-8">
            <li class="flex gap-6 group">
              <span class="flex-none w-10 h-10 rounded-xl bg-amber-500 flex items-center justify-center text-olive-950 font-bold font-mono transition-transform group-hover:scale-110">A</span>
              <div>
                <strong class="text-white text-lg block mb-1">The Local Chapter</strong>
                <p class="text-olive-300">Autonomous nodes making decisions based on the needs of physical neighborhoods.</p>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flex gap-6 group">
              <span class="flex-none w-10 h-10 rounded-xl bg-amber-500 flex items-center justify-center text-olive-950 font-bold font-mono transition-transform group-hover:scale-110">B</span>
              <div>
                <strong class="text-white text-lg block mb-1">The Agora App</strong>
                <p class="text-olive-300">A functional “social app” that facilitates organizing and disincentivizes digital distraction.</p>
              </div>
            </li>
            <li class="flex gap-6 group">
              <span class="flex-none w-10 h-10 rounded-xl bg-amber-500 flex items-center justify-center text-olive-950 font-bold font-mono transition-transform group-hover:scale-110">C</span>
              <div>
                <strong class="text-white text-lg block mb-1">The Commons</strong>
                <p class="text-olive-300">Prioritizing physical spaces—parks, halls, and workshops—outside the reach of the market.</p>
              </div>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-4">
          <h2 class="text-xs font-mono font-bold text-amber-600 uppercase tracking-widest">5. Platform Socialism</h2>
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold text-olive-950 tracking-tight">
            Most apps are designed to keep you inside them. <span class="text-amber-700">The Agora App</span> is designed to push you out.
          </h3>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed">
            By functioning as a utilitarian bulletin board, it strips away the dopamine loops of modern social media, leaving only a tool for real connection and collective action. We use digital tools to transcend the limitations of digital life.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-6">
          <h2 class="text-xs font-mono font-bold text-amber-600 uppercase tracking-widest">6. Rebuilding Trust</h2>
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-bold text-olive-950 tracking-tight"></h3>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed">
            The crisis of community is also a crisis of <strong>trust</strong>. We need to rebuild trust in ourselves, in each other, and perhaps most importantly, in collective action. Capitalism offers a false sense of individual autonomy through the illusion of personal choice. In contrast, participating in a collective project requires us to submit some of our autonomy for the sake of group discipline.
          </p>
          <p class="text-olive-800 leading-relaxed">
            For an alienated individual who's been raised to make a fetish of their individuality, this can be a frightening prospect. When we have so little experience of collective action, it’s easy to mistake group discipline for authoritarianism.
          </p>
          <p class="text-olive-950 font-bold text-xl border-l-4 border-olive-900 pl-8 my-10 py-2 leading-snug">
            We can't combat that fear through education, only through a slowly increasing level of experience with the value and the power of collective action.           </p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <footer class="pt-16 border-t border-olive-200">
        <div class="bg-olive-900 p-10 rounded-[2.5rem] shadow-xl flex flex-col md:flex-row justify-between items-center gap-8">
          <div class="text-center md:text-left space-y-1">
            <p class="text-[10px] text-amber-400 uppercase font-mono tracking-[0.3em] font-bold">Deep Dive</p>
            <h4 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white tracking-tight">Ready to meet the Quorum?</h4>
          </div>
          <a href="/quorum" class="bg-amber-600 text-white px-10 py-4 rounded-full font-bold hover:bg-amber-500 transition shadow-lg shadow-amber-600/20 active:scale-95 text-sm uppercase tracking-widest">
            Internal Governance &rarr;
          </a>
        </div>
      </footer>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>